00:01:21.960 --> 00:01:25.130
Geographically, the U.S. was a huge country
with all the resources necessary for an industrial

00:01:25.130 --> 00:01:26.130
boom.

00:01:26.130 --> 00:01:28.110
Like, we had coal, and iron and, later, oil.

00:01:28.110 --> 00:01:31.909
Initially we had water to power our factories,
later replaced by coal.

00:01:31.909 --> 00:01:37.000
And we had amber waves of grain to feed our
growing population which leads to the Demography.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:43.049
America’s population grew from 40 million
in 1870 to 76 million in 1900 and 1/3 of that

00:01:43.049 --> 00:01:44.659
growth was due to immigration.

00:01:44.659 --> 00:01:46.799
Which is good for economies.

00:01:46.799 --> 00:01:51.380
Many of these immigrants flooded the burgeoning
cities, as America shifted from being an agrarian

00:01:51.380 --> 00:01:54.060
rural nation to being an industrial, urban
one.

00:01:54.060 --> 00:01:58.090
Like, New York City became the center of commerce
and finance and by 1898 it had a population

00:01:58.090 --> 00:02:00.229
of 3.4 million people.

00:02:00.229 --> 00:02:02.700
And the industrial heartland was in the Great
Lakes region.

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:07.880
Chicago became the second largest city by
1900, Cleveland became a leader in oil refining,

00:02:07.880 --> 00:02:10.729
and Pittsburgh was a center of iron and steel
production.

00:02:10.729 --> 00:02:14.400
And even today, the great city of Pittsburgh
still employs 53 Steelers.

00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:16.060
Last but not least was the Law.

00:02:16.060 --> 00:02:20.069
The Constitution and its commerce clause made
the U.S. a single area of commerce – like

00:02:20.069 --> 00:02:21.830
a giant customs union.

00:02:21.830 --> 00:02:26.200
And, as we’ll see in a bit the Supreme Court
interpreted the laws in a very business friendly

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:27.200
way.

00:02:27.200 --> 00:02:30.880
Also, the American constitution protects patents,
which encourag4B-es invention and innovation,

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:31.880
or at least it used to.

00:02:31.880 --> 00:02:36.090
And despite what Ayn Rand would tell you,
the American government played a role in American

00:02:36.090 --> 00:02:41.120
economic growth by putting up high tariffs,
especially on steel, giving massive land grants

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:44.160
to railroads and by putting Native Americans
on reservations.

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:46.080
Also, foreigners played an important role.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:49.910
They invested their capital and involved Americans
in their economic scandals like the one that

00:02:49.910 --> 00:02:51.790
led to a depression in 1893.

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:56.050
The U.S. was at the time was seen by Europeans
as a developing economy; and investments in

00:02:56.050 --> 00:02:59.240
America offered much higher returns than those
available in Europe.

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:01.239
And the changes we’re talking about here
were massive.

00:03:01.239 --> 00:03:05.690
In 1880, for the first time, a majority of
the workforce worked in non-farming jobs.

00:03:05.690 --> 00:03:10.880
By 1890 2/3 of Americans worked for wages,
rather than farming or owning their own businesses.

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:17.010
And, by 1913 the United States produced 1/3
of the world’s total industrial output.

