00:03:27.930 --> 00:03:31.019
Although we tend to forget about them here
in the U.S., because our passenger rail system

00:03:31.019 --> 00:03:35.590
sucks, railroads were one of the keys to America’s
19th century industrial success.

00:03:35.590 --> 00:03:38.950
Railroads increased commerce and integrated
the American market, which allowed national

00:03:38.950 --> 00:03:42.980
brands to emerge, like Ivory Soap and A&amp;P
Grocery Stores.

00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:46.731
But railroads changed and improved our economy
in less obvious ways, too: For instance, they

00:03:46.731 --> 00:03:50.480
gave us time zones, which were created by
the major railroad companies to make shipping

00:03:50.480 --> 00:03:52.580
and passenger transport more standard.

00:03:52.580 --> 00:03:56.120
Also because he recognized the importance
of telling time, a railroad agent named Richard

00:03:56.120 --> 00:04:00.650
Warren Sears turned a $50 dollar investment
in watches into an enormous mail order empire,

00:04:00.650 --> 00:04:05.569
and railroads made it possible for him--and
his eventual partner Roebuck--to ship watches,

00:04:05.569 --> 00:04:10.629
and then jewelry, and then pretty much everything,
including unconstructed freaking houses throughout

00:04:10.629 --> 00:04:11.629
the country.

00:04:11.629 --> 00:04:13.879
Railroads were also the first modern corporations.

00:04:13.879 --> 00:04:17.449
These companies were large, they had many
employees, they spanned the country.

00:04:17.449 --> 00:04:22.510
And that meant they needed to invent organizational
methods, including the middle manager--supervisors

00:04:22.510 --> 00:04:24.190
to supervise supervisors.

00:04:24.190 --> 00:04:28.820
And for the first time, the owners of a company
were not always day-to-day managers, because

00:04:28.820 --> 00:04:31.160
railroads were among the first publicly traded
corporations.

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:34.540
They needed a lot of capital to build tracks
and stations, so they sold shares in

00:04:34.540 --> 00:04:38.220
the company in order to raise that money,
which shares could then be bought and sold

00:04:38.220 --> 00:04:39.220
by the public.

00:04:39.220 --> 00:04:43.060
And that is how railroads created the first
captains of industry, like Cornelius “They

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:47.640
Named a University after Me” Vanderbilt
and Andrew “Me Too” Carnegie (Mellon)

00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:50.790
and Leland “I Named a University After My
Son” Stanford.

00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:54.600
The Railroad business was also emblematic
of the partnership between the national government

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:55.600
and industry.

00:04:55.600 --> 00:04:58.800
The Transcontinental Railroad, after all,
wouldn’t have existed without Congressional

00:04:58.800 --> 00:05:02.260
legislation, federal land grants, and government
sponsored bond issues.

